        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Canada meets Europe</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: New Canadian Prime Minister Mark Carney is seeking alliances in Europe to manage Trump and the trade war with the US.</strong></p>

          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Canadian PM Mark Carney met President Macron in Paris on <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-18-03-2025-h3-3-his-first-foreign-visit" target="_blank">his first foreign visit</a>, seeking alliances amid President Trump’s tariff threats. Carney will next visit London for talks with UK Prime Minister Keir Starmer and King Charles III. Carney deliberately chose the two European cities that shaped Canada’s early existence.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Carney emphasized that Canada was built on the bedrock of French, English, and Indigenous peoples. While avoiding direct criticism of Trump, Macron stated that tariffs fuel inflation and harm economic integration. Trump has already imposed tariffs on Canadian steel and aluminum and threatened new ones on all Canadian goods starting April 2.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Carney, a former Bank of England governor, has no immediate plans to visit Washington but hopes to speak with Trump soon. The leaders discussed Ukraine, with Carney inviting President Zelenskyy to the upcoming G7 summit in Canada. Carney is expected to call an election at the end of the week, with Trump’s trade war being the focal point of the 2025 Canadian elections.</p>
        </mj-text>
