          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">What is passportization?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/russian-passports-issued-foreign-citizens.png" alt="Russian passports are issued to foreign citizens" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Russian passports are issued to foreign citizens. Credits: Sergei Vedyashkin / Moskva News Agency</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">​​Passportization is a state's strategy for <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-18-03-2025-f1-6-granting-nationality-to-foreign-citizens" target="_blank">granting nationality to foreign citizens</a>. Sometimes, this can extend influence and even destabilize regions. This practice has gained prominence in Russia's actions in areas like Georgia, Moldova, and Ukraine. Russia made a simplified citizenship process for some citizens in Russia and aims to assert control over breakaway territories like Abkhazia, South Ossetia, Transnistria, and Eastern Ukraine.
</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          The goal is to give a pretext to justify intervention to protect its citizens abroad. Others raised points that many European countries, such as Italy, give citizenship to those of Italian lineage for up to 4 or 5 generations. Many recipients do not vote and mainly use it to live in the EU. Many European countries do it more to raise the birthrate or attract economic capital.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          There are speculations that Hungary does it for many ethnic Hungarians beyond its borders for the same reason. Countries like Slovakia had strict dual citizenship for this reason. Another issue with passportization is that Russia specifically implemented this process in countries where it wanted to influence fewer ethnic Russians. There were plenty of legitimate claims of Russian minorities being persecuted in countries such as the Baltic States and Kazakhstan that were not taken into as much consideration.</p>
          
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
